\par Inside the Peabody Museum of Natural History, there stands a room, an entire room, whose walls are adorned with faithful reproductions of the Maya murals at Bonampak. Although the precise historical texture of the mural
s remains a matter of some conjecture, archeologists and epigraphers have managed to reconstruct the narrative they contain with an adequate degree of scientific certainty. The sequence of murals represents a ritualized war. They begin and end with trumpe
ting processions of musicians and dancers who prepare the way for conquest and victory. The battle itself is depicted in gruesome detail. But perhaps the most striking scene represents the battle\rquote 
s aftermath. On a series of temple steps that ascend toward a
n arching sky filled with gods, the actors in this very real drama stand in their finery and in their misery. At the base of the temple a line of victorious warriors, in ritual masquerade, hold blood spattered spears, their eyes directed to the steps abov
e
. On those upper steps, prisoners lie prostrate, some dead, their severed heads rolling earthward, others still living, with blood pouring from severed finger-tips and open wounds. On the top step, just below the divine canopy, stands the warrior chief an
d his attendants; and before that lord, a naked prisoner kneels, his arms outstretched, perhaps in a plea for his life.}{\cs20\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \s19\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\nooverflow\faroman\rin0\lin0\itap0 
