\par In recent years, scholars have come to regard the Ancient Maya as a so-called \'93great people.\'94 Their writing, their sculpture, their a
rt and their calligraphy, their poetry and drama, all signs of a powerful and dynamically literate culture. But here, in the remains of Maya art, we find the intersection of culture and class; for it was not the culture as a whole that produced the great 
works of art and literature that we associate with the Maya, but a single strata; the ruling class. And this was not art for art\rquote 
s sake. Quite the contrary. Maya iconography celebrate the rulers, their collaborators, and their victories in warfare and conqu
est. Perhaps our modern minds find this idea difficult; the idea that such powerful products of the life of the spirit find their legitimacy by legitimizing power and slaughter.  Perhaps, were we less circumspect in our language than we should be, we migh
t call the images in Maya art,--well, if not \'93primitive\'94, then at the very least, \'93barbaric\'94. And perhaps they are. But who are the barbarians? 
\par 
\par The great works of Maya iconography may have been the product of an elite within the culture, but that elite, d
evoting its time to cultivating its sense of beauty and drama, studying the movements of the stars and the processions in the heavens, spinning the grand mythologies contained in the }{\i\fs24 Popol Vuh}{\fs24 
,--that elite lived in palaces built by human hands; smoked tobacco harvested by peasants; ate corn and drank chocolate that it received in tribute from its subjects and servants and slaves. 
\par 
